<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="126" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,394,887]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,394,419]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Description.</emphasis>
Forewing length: Wingspan: 
<quantity box="[633,758,394,419]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.65" metricValueMax="2.8" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" unit="mm" value="26.5" valueMax="28.0" valueMin="25.0">25–28 mm</quantity>
. The upperside ground colour is deep fiery orange or bright orange, with black apex and outer margin on the forewing. The width of the black margin is variable but it tapers down towards the tornus and along to costa. The hindwing also has a black border between the apex and the tornus and a black band or black scaling along the inner margin. The underside is uniformic paler orange with a narrow, black marginal line framing both wings, the line along the forewing costa has a few small black spots. Black dusting appears all over the underside more densely along the forewing costa and the sub-marginal area of both wings. The dorsal side of the body is orange and brown, whereas the ventral side is pale orange. The legs and the antennae are black ringed with white. The eyes are dark chocolate brown or black, large and smooth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,394,887]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,316,682,707]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Genitalia.</emphasis>
The general appearence of the genitalic armature is unique, placing the genus near 
<taxonomicName box="[1252,1388,683,707]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Pseuderesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1252,1388,683,707]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Pseuderesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,281,719,742]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Eresiomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,281,719,742]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">Eresiomera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The tegumen is shield-shaped, resembling an irregular hexagon from anteroposterior view. The uncus is not bifid, the sub-unci missing and the valvae are paralelogram-shaped. The aedeagus is of unique shape, branching and the dorsal projection is rather weakly sclerotised. Its distal end is strongly recurved (
<figureCitation box="[1266,1343,790,815]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1570,1592]" captionTargetBox="[199,1403,886,1425]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[152,1434,844,1547]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Comparison of male genitalic armature between Parasiomera, Pseuderesia and Eresiomera: P. pa r ad ox a (lectotype) A—valvae (caudal view), D—aedeagus (lateral view); P. eleaza B—valvae (caudal view), E—aedeagus (lateral view); E. bicolor C—valvae (caudal view), F—aedeagus (lateral view) (the latter two were re-drawn from Stempffer’s original (1967) where no scale was included)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238188/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="126">
Figs. 
<number box="[1330,1343,791,815]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
A,D, 
<number box="[1406,1422,790,815]" pageId="2" pageNumber="126" value="6.0">6</number>
). Female genitalia are rather simple with medium sized, slightly oval bursa copulatrix, broad ductus bursae, rather strongly sclerotised rounded lamellae, broad papillae analis and short, gently curving apophyses posteriores.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
